        <div id="page-intro">
            <h1>Cross-project bug tracking</h1>
            <p>
                <img src="images/bugs/main-image.jpg" alt="Collaborate with free software communities." /></p>
                <p class="intro-text">
<strong>When projects share free software code they share its bugs.</strong> Inevitably, the same bug is reported and discussed in  different places.</p>
                <p class="intro-text">
<strong>Launchpad brings the discussion to you:</strong> on one page you can see how the bug affects different communities, whether they're tracking the bug in Launchpad, Bugzilla, Trac, Sourceforge, or elsewhere. You can even share a comment history across project-boundaries, bringing everyone together to find a fix.</p>

            <div id="link-holder"><a href="https://bugs.launchpad.net/">Visit Launchpad Bugs &gt;</a><br /><a href="https://launchpad.net/projects/+new">Add your project to Launchpad &gt;</a></div>
        </div>
        <div id="page-intro-bottom"></div>
        <ul id="secondary-navigation">
            <li class="button-next">
                <a href="branch-hosting-tracking" accesskey="d" tabindex="2">Next</a>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <div id="further-information">
            <div class="furthur-information-block">
                <div class="furthur-information-block-top"></div>
                <div class="furthur-information-block-mid">
                    <div class="block">
                        <h3>Shared bug reports, independent statuses</h3>
                        <h4>By sharing bug reports and their comment histories across communities, Launchpad lets everyone who&rsquo;s interested work together to find a fix.</h4>
                        <p class="screen-holder">
                            <img src="images/bugs/1.png" alt="Shared bug reports, independent statuses" width="428" height="311" />                        </p>
                        <p>
Each group &mdash; whether projects or distributions &mdash; can track how the bug affects them by recording their own status, importance and assignee.
</p><p>
There&rsquo;s even a &ldquo;Bugs fixed elsewhere&rdquo; report that shows which of your bugs are marked fixed in other communities, so you know where to look for low-hanging fruit.
</p><p>
<strong>As an example:</strong> someone discovers a Python bug while using Ubuntu&rsquo;s Twisted package. While each community &mdash; Ubuntu, Twisted and Python &mdash; tracks the bug independently, Launchpad brings the bug statuses and conversations together into a single collaborative effort to fix the problem for everyone.
                        </p>
<p>
<strong>Launchpad works with these external bug trackers:</strong> Bugzilla, Trac, Sourceforge, Roundup, Mantis, RT and Debian BTS. More to come.
</p>                          
                    </div>
                    <div class="block odd">
                        <h3>Delegate triage and planning</h3>
                        <h4>Delegate day to day bug management to trusted members of your project community.</h4>
                        <p class="screen-holder">
                            <img src="images/bugs/2.jpg" alt="Bugs fixed elsewhere" width="428" height="311" />                        </p>
                        <p>
                        The Bug Supervisor role is a convenient way to delegate bug management to a team or individual. They can set each bug&rsquo;s importance and target them to future releases.</p>
                        <p>You can manage permissions in the bug tracker to balance the efficiency of an open community with the control of careful delegation. Stay on top of security issues by assigning a dedicated Security Contact and keep security bugs private until you&rsquo;ve released a fix.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="clear"></div>
                </div>
                <div class="furthur-information-block-bot"></div>
            </div>
            <div class="furthur-information-block">
                <div class="furthur-information-block-top"></div>
                <div class="furthur-information-block-mid">
                    <div class="block">
                        <h3>Bugs by email</h3>
                        <h4>Report, edit, assign and target bugs by email.</h4>
                        <p class="screen-holder">
                            <img src="images/bugs/3.png" alt="Bug tracker email interface" width="428" height="311" />                        </p>
                        <p>
                            If you prefer, you can manage bug reports entirely through your mail client.
</p><p>
Stay informed of the bugs that interest you with email and Atom feed subscriptions. Launchpad sends email updates to everyone who&rsquo;s interested in a bug, such as the initial reporter or the person assigned to work on a fix. You can also subscribe to individual bugs or all the bugs associated with a particular project or distribution package. Bug mail goes both ways: file new bugs, make comments, update statuses, add attachments and more by email.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="block odd">
                        <h3>Found a fix? Publish a branch</h3>
                        <h4>You no longer need to swap dead patches in bug comments. Instead, link bug reports directly to Bazaar branches of code containing the latest version of your fix.</h4>
                        <p class="screen-holder">
                            <img src="images/bugs/5.png" alt="Found a fix? Upload a branch" />
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Other community members can download your branches and test them without the hassle of applying patches. Thanks to Bazaar, it&rsquo;s easy to merge the branch containing your bug fix into your project&rsquo;s trunk. Bazaar branches are like "living patches" &mdash; a single URL points to the latest version of the fix and a single command merges it into your trunk branch.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="clear"></div>
                </div>
                <div class="furthur-information-block-bot"></div>
